review.itemreviewed: Stansbury Print ALLIED Down Tight - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I wanted a pair of "puffer" style pants after seeing some super heavy duty options from mountain hardwear. I came across these and thought that these were more suitable to wear out and about, way more affordable, and just super aesthetic overall. Since the back half are normal legging material in solid black, and the front are down lined, they are super warm without being too much of a michelin marshmallow puff. The crotch area does puff out a bit just a bit because of the seam, so if you are camel conscious - that is worth mentioning. I have a very pear shaped body and these fit flattering enough for me, and sit high waisted. They are also incredibly cozy and comfortable, most importantly they are so warm! I wore these while snow shoveling and was standing in 3 foot snow drifts at times, my legs did not get cold or feel wet at all the entire time. They also flex well so I found them very easy to move in. These are an awesome addition to my winter wardrobe & I would probably buy them in more color variations.

Fun fact: you can also track where the down in your pants down came from!
review.name: Amazing! These keep me so warm!

review.itemreviewed: Stansbury Print ALLIED Down Tight - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I have a few of these pants from various years in a few different colors (Hey Backcountry- coffee brown again please and Navy next year!). This pink color certainly stands out. It pairs well with my Patagonia better sweater in a berry color. They are not bulky at all and give me a nice silhouette. Note that the down is only on the front panel and the back is knit, which IMO keeps one from looking like the Michelin man. I'm 5'2 and they are the perfect length so if you are a tall person they may be more like an ankle pant. These pants hold up well without losing feathers nor losing their shape. I wear them over smooth leggings almost every day for dog walks and when I get home from work to lounge in- great for keeping the heat a little lower to save on electric). I wash every so often on delicate and dry in the dryer with dryer balls on low heat for a few cycles. These are also cozy under a waterproof shell for cold. rainy weather. The fall/winter 2023-2024 pants have a diagonal stitch baffle to keep feathers evenly distributed, whereas past years have had a straight stitch. I prefer the straight across stitch because I think it is a cleaner look, but that is just me being annoyingly picky about aesthetics. Overall I would highly recommend these pants, and the matching skirt over leggings is great too (though I sized up to a small for that). Though they are an investment, it's a fair price point for what you get- I've never been poked by feathers or really lost many, and the down is responsibly sourced. 
Great for cold walks, dog walks, skiing/outdoor sports, camping/hiking, Eagles games, hanging out watching your kids sports in freezing cold and ice hockey rinks, Apres-ski, layering over a base layer for extra warmth, and keeping warm when you go to people's houses who refuse to up the thermostat past 65 in the winter.
review.name: warm pant, worth the investment

review.reviewBody: I have been on the hunt for rain pants that fit and with pockets. I was excited about these as tried on a medium in a store and thought the small would be perfect so ordered them. I was surprised to see a mesh lining as may have missed that in the description. I like the side bottom zipper and Velcro strap idea but won't reach my shoes so not super useful for me. I am sad to say I may need to return them. review.reviewBody: Got an ohm to help my belayer, but didn't know how much it would help. I'm a bigger guy, about 285, and my climbing friends are all in the 140-200 range. Took a couple test falls and my belayer barely moved, had confident control. Falls changed from meeting them at the 1st bolt, to barely a bunny hop. Will not climb without this thing anymore.
review.name: Game changer for bigger climbers

review.reviewBody:
This device adds friction to the rope system, and that goes both ways.  This is definitely adds security when a sport climb is hard off the start with a big weight difference between climber and belayer.  When the route is stepper or has a low bulge, the rope hangs in the friction groove when slack.  I’ve been short roped when climbing and clipping from this.  Also, had a loop of rope build up between the Ohm and the second QuickDraw because the slack would fall thru the Ohm, down to my belayer.

The Ohm does what it’s suppose to do, but it has hindered my performance, even high up on a right.  Maybe extending it will help, but when you’re already 6 bolts up, it is a little too late for that.  Not for the performance minded and a great way to blow an onsite.
review.name: Giveth and Taketh

review.reviewBody: This thing has made my (a <100lb female) climbing trips with men so much safer, easier, less stressful, and more fulfilling. Now both parties can really push it and not worry about taking falls. Lowering men is 1000x easier as well where I would previously struggle to stay grounded or to lower them at a consistent pace.
review.name: I’m small he’s big

review.reviewBody: If you have a big weight difference between the belayer and climber GET THIS! It's incredible how much force this takes off the belayer on a fall! I weight 50lbs less than my partner and it has made belaying them so much safer and comfortable. Easy to use once you understand the setup, 1st clip and it's done. No more flying feet in the air when your climber falls!
review.name: WORTH THE MONEY!!

review.reviewBody: My girlfriend is a good 60lbs lighter than me without gear. This does it's job and helps her be more confident.  We don't use it as much anymore because it's helped train her confidence and she feels good without it.
review.name: Does what it should

review.reviewBody: I am older now.  I do not wear the shoes so tight I need to remove them after every climb. However, these shoes do everything I need them to do for indoor climbing. I love the colors, I love the security I feel on each rock, I love the stability and balance I feel with these shoes.  I would give them a 5 except they crunch up a bit at the  top end of my laces.  I think if they ever get straight they would get a 5.5, but until then a a four (4 1/2).  I do love them, and the price was good.
review.name: love them

review.reviewBody:
I have a long narrow foot.  This shoe was listed on the La Sportiva charts as being the narrowest shoe.  I have had several La Sportiva climbing shoes and wear a 41 (US 9.5).  I wear a street shoe of US 10 - Womans.  I don't like my shoes to be terribly uncomfortable but still want them snug enough once they break in.   I was disappointed because even with tightening this down as much as possible, it was gapping around the front of my ankle and all around the top of my toes.  It's for this reason that I usually stick with woman's specific shoes - maybe they'd be good for a narrow man foot with meaty toes and beefy ankles. 
   
The shoe seems to measure longer than some of my others too - even though this is supposed to be aggressive.  It was not terribly uncomfortable for a brand new, aggressive shoe but just not a snug fit.  So regarding product fit -  they are smaller than 'true to size' for a street shoe - but "run large" when compared other La Sportiva climbing shoes of the same size. 

I climbed two indoor routes. They handled ok except by the end the laces were already untied.  I was skeptical about the laces because I take my more aggressive shoes off between climbs and didn't want to take the time to tie and untie them.  But the description made them sound like they would work better than standard laces - which they do pull through easily - but they're not easier to lace up.   So with much disappointment I returned them after only two climbs.
review.name: Not impressed - wide - laces untie
comment: Hey Brandy! Sorry these didn't work for you, I too have a pair of climbing shoes I was really excited about, but they have been a bit disappointing, and I know it's frustrating. I will email in to follow up as well!

review.reviewBody: If I’m going on a climbing trip and I could only pack one pair of shoes, the Muiras would be the climbing shoes I would choose. They keep me standing on micro-edges with ease, excel at pocket climbing, stick to slabs, good for steep climbing, and can heel-hook. The laces make them work in cracks, however I wouldn’t wear these for a long crack climb as the narrow toe box can hurt my toes after a long period of time. I like how the rubber is durable and lasts for a long time. I have narrow, low volume feet so having the laces help me adjust the fit of the shoe to my feet.
review.name: My “one shoe that can do it all”

review.reviewBody: I love any type of climbing from bouldewing to trad. I choose my climbing shoes depending on what I'm climbing. When I go bouldering and the business is about precision on granite, the Miura is the shoe I grab. They are my shoes for sending hard. Edges like razor blades, very confortable and precise. My favorite shoes until the TC pro came to the market. I don't use them for wide cracks.  But bouldering in the Valley on those sleek footholds and finger cracks Miura is the shoe for it!!!!
review.name: Perfect for send projects!!!

review.reviewBody: This is an awesome climbing shoe in terms of performance, but if you are wearing this outdoor on a hot day, it is unbearably uncomfortable you the point you cannot climb in it. Maybe it might be better if you size up, but I know these are my correct size because I wear the TC Pros in the same size which are comfy. I can?t wear these shoes for even moderate length single pitch routes for a half day sometimes. They are super sticky and aggressive when you?re actually on the wall though.
review.name: Aggressive but unbearably uncomfy
comment: Diane/Alaina: Go with the Miura VS womens and size up 1/2 size.  You might lose 5% performance, but your toes will thank you.  I wear 44.5 in virtually all my La Sportivas, but must go with 45 in the Miura VS.  Wowzers, what edging!  Plus the VS model keeps its aggressive downturn.

Hey Diane, this sounds like my problem too. Have you ever found a shoe that performs similarly with the sticky/aggressive precise technical edging but doesn't kill the toes? I'm still searching for one that's not too far off from Miuras in performance and climbing style, but hurts less.

review.reviewBody: I actually have no idea how many pairs of Miuras I have owned over the years. Lots and lots...and lots is all I can say. I have worn them all over the place and have climbed many types of stone with them. From Indian Creek splitters to techy face climbing to alpine granite...they are amazing! I wore them on first ascents in Wadi Rum, Patagonia, Morocco, the Buggaboos.. They are absolutely my favorite shoe. And they perform so well that I don't have to wear them super tight. Maybe that is the best reason to get a pair of these! They don't have to hurt to be awesome!
review.name: The best shoe ever!!

review.reviewBody: I bought these for a more comfortable fit over the more downturned shoes (ie kataki, solutions) for long sport climbs and multi pitch.  After years of aggressive shoes, I am quite suprised with how well these shoes perform on tiny foot holds and overhangs. The addition of fabric at the heel is a nice touch.
review.name: Great laceup

review.reviewBody: This is the fourth pair of Miura lace-ups I've owned, and I really love these shoes. The newest version seems to have some gapping around the ankle that is new, with a little bit more fabric than previous versions - but on the other hand, doesn't have the digging into the back of the ankle at the achilles problem that previous versions did for me. Overall a great aggressive shoe, though I'd like a tighter fit around the upper forefoot/ankle.
review.name: Great sending shoes - a little different fit

review.reviewBody: These are the perfect shoe for advanced climbers who don’t want to wreck their feet with the curve of the Solution shoe. I love the stylish print, a huge upgrade from the old muiras which were just tan. I highly recommend this shoe!!
review.name: Great shoe

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: I am a 5 foot 10 inches tall female side sleeper who moves around a lot in my sleep and found the Etherlight XT WL to be the most comfortable sleeping mat I have ever owned. It is easy to inflate & being tapered, fits better in the tent when there are 2 of us. It has reduced noise but still does make a little bit of rustling sounds when I am changing my position. Love that the pillow can be "locked" to the mattress as well. I am based in New Zealand where the weather can range from freezing cold to very warm. I would be very careful with making sure the ground is free from any lumps & bumps under my tent OR I put some spare clothes between the mat and my tent floor for extra protection & warmth. Reviewed on 25 May 2024.
review.name: Tall woman review

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody:
After 30 nights of use, leaks started developing on the rims of the circular dimple buttons, or what some people call the spot welds. The first night it started leaking, it took 9 hours for my butt to touch the ground. The second night it took 3 hours. I tried searching for the leak 3 separate times, finding and patching only 1 leak each time. But after fixing the 3 leaks, it's still leaking somewhere and it's now accelerated. Now it only takes 1 hour for my butt to touch the ground, so it seems that the problem has become worse. I've also run out of the 3 large rectangular patches that came with the mattress. Only the smaller circular patches remain but they're too small to cover the dimples. So I've given up on repairing.

Although the first 30 nights sleeping on this mattress was really comfortable due to it being deeper than most other brands.
review.name: Comfortable but leaks

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] This is my second one of these actually. My previous one eventually got a leak. But it has treated me well. I got the women’s version cuz I’m short and always cold so I like the extra insulation. Still gets a bit cold in below freezing temps, but summer camping it does well. I like the size and shape and ease of inflating and deflating. I would def recommend. Slightly higher R rating would really make it perfect.
review.name: Great mat

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] Amazing Sleeping pad! I bought this for my trip to the Boundary Waters Canoe Area Wilderness. It is so light and compact. The shipping was very quick and easy. I ordered it last second and it came sooner than expected. The size and width is perfect!
review.name: LOVE

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: I use this sleeping pad for backpacking and bicycle camping. It is very comfortable, but a little noisy, but my husband and I have gotten used to it. It does take a little longer to blow up (more like 6-8 bags) but the size and comfort is worth it. I love the two way air valve so that as you're inflating it, the air you have already put in it stays put. To deflate, just open the valve and the air whooshes out. I have used it in 30 degree weather and have had no cold penetration through the pad. My only complaint is the pillow lock system. I bought a Aeros Ultralight pillow and applied the sticky Velcro-type pieces. It worked great for about three trips. But now the sticky pieces have traveled all around and the pillow won't stay on the pad. I don't know if this is a pillow or a pad problem but that was very disappointing. But ,the pad has worked great so far, and packs up small, so five stars for the pad, but one star for the pillow system.
review.name: The sleeping pad is great but not the pillow lock system

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody:
I'm torn on picking a star review. Maybe I should have realized from the r rating that it would not be warm enough. But it is so cold that it is completely useless to me without another piece of gear (thermarest z-lite foam pad) which makes me want to give it one star. The description talks about its insulation so I thought it would be at least somewhat functional. 

You can feel the cold are beneath you. I started noticing it when temperatures got into the low 50s. It was annoying but tolerable. Lower than that, it is really unpleasant. I tried putting a reflective foam pad underneath and that didn't help, still too cold. If I put the pad on top, it is warm enough. But then I start wondering why I'm using two pieces of gear instead of just buying a better inflatable pad. I've talked to someone else who also felt the cold air when he tried it, so it's not just me. If you only backpack in very warm temperatures this pad would be fine but otherwise, it's not worth it. 

Also, it is noisy. It sounds like inner tubes rubbing against each other whenever you move on it.

Temperate aside, it is very light and quite cushy. I really wanted to like this pad but it is not warm enough for the Pacific Northwest, even in the summer.
review.name: Comfy, but so cold

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: This is hands down the most comfortable sleeping pad I’ve owed. The stuff sack makes blowing it up easy and I love that you can attach an inflatable pillow to it. I’m so disappointed in how noisy it is though. I toss and turn a lot and everyone I’ve ever shared a tent with complains about how loud it is (and it also wakes me up when I move). If anyone has suggestions on how to make it *not* noisy, I’m all ears because others don’t seem to have this issue?
review.name: So comfy but OMG noisy

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: Despite the claim that this pad is quiet, it’s not. I’m not sure what the problem is but I disturbed my friends who were sleeping in separate tents but close by. We had small camp sites in a kayaking expedition and for three weeks it didn’t make me popular! It could have been my tent bottom, but even testing it after I got home with a pad cover, it was still too noisy. I had to sell it on.
review.name: Noisy

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I tried this pad in my living room for a couple hours. It is very comfortable and I like the width and the shape. I don't feel like I'm going to roll off easily. It is a bit heavy but it's insulated and a wide mat so I'm willing to have those few extra ounces for comfortable sleep. Looking forward to doing a proper trip with it!
review.name: Awesome pad!

review.itemreviewed: Ether Light XT Insulated Sleeping Pad - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I’ve tried many sleeping pads and this is my favorite by far. Totally worth the money for maximum comfort and minimal weight. Highly recommended for backcountry backpacking and camping. Also sets up and packs down fast & easy.
review.name: My favorite- worth every penny

review.itemreviewed: Capilene Cool Daily Graphic Short-Sleeve Shirt - Women's
review.reviewBody: I absolutely love everything about this shirt, but it arrived damaged. When I started the return there is no way to request an exchange for a replacement. So disappointed because I truly live the shirt and the shorts that go with it. Without the shirt, the shorts are going back too.
review.name: Fabulous but damaged

review.itemreviewed: Capilene Cool Daily Graphic Short-Sleeve Shirt - Women's
review.reviewBody: Every time I tried to find a non-cotton t-shirt to have something I could travel in, they were all too uncomfortable.   They had v or scoop necklines and/or tiny cap sleeves (no, I sunburn easily and I hate it when my sweaty chin and neck can touch my sweaty chest with no material in-between), they didn't breathe and/or felt stiff and scratchy or they didn't fit right.  I'm short and pudgy and I'm also on the spectrum and am really picky about how clothing feels on my body.  I was at an REI and decided to, sigh, once again try on some performance shirts, expecting that I still wouldn't find anything I could stand.  I pulled this grey one over my head and instantly stopped in shock.  It felt great!  Even though it was the most expensive t-shirt I tried on that day, I bought it and then later found three more in XL left in stock here at Backcountry and bought those too.  By the way, I have noticed that the inside  seams that aren't covered feel slightly scratchy against my skin--better than others, but I wish the thread was softer or that they'd been able to cover more of the seams.   I wonder if I would like the plain colored ones also?   I usually prefer t-shirts that have decoration.   At last I will have t-shirts for travel that I can wash in a sink and dry overnight and they're so light weight and comfortable too!    Thank you, Patagonia!
review.name: THIS is the shirt I've wanted for years

review.itemreviewed: Capilene Cool Daily Graphic Short-Sleeve Shirt - Women's
review.reviewBody: What a great shirt! It was so soft and so comfortable to wear. It kept me dry during my hike. The weather was a little cool but the shirt did it’s thing. It was a perfect shirt for what I needed it for and I really like the color.
review.name: So soft & so comfortable!

review.reviewBody: After buying a number of mediocre shorts in the moderate price range and not being very happy with the pad and overall quality and comfort I decided to try these. Boy what a difference, the fit and comfort are great and finally a pad that lets me stay in the saddle all day. They are expensive but if they hold up it will be money well spent.
review.name: Very comfortable

review.reviewBody: A former teammate recommended Giordana to replace our aging team kits. Now that we are retired from the local amateur crash fests, it was time for some upgrades. The bibs fit like a glove. Great chamois. Love the wide straps. Thankfully purchased two as they are my go to. Super happy thus far.
review.name: Great Recommendation

review.reviewBody: Though on the pricy side, I've made an exception for these bib shorts. For me, by far the most comfortable bibs I own. I like the slightly longer leg of this bib and the wider bib strap. The first pair lasted 3 seasons with before showing signs of wear, though they were still comfortable.
review.name: On My Second Set

review.reviewBody: I researched many bibs and decided to go with these. You'd have to prove it to me to make me believe there is a better pair on the market. The comfort and feel is excellent and super lightweight. For me there is no need to try any other brand.
review.name: Best bibs I've ever owned

review.reviewBody:
*initial impression, subject to change.

After a few more rides: I may bump this up a star. The product literature suggested using without chamois creme, claiming it's unnecessary. It tried it without, and indeed it worked out well.  I'll go for some longer rides without just to be sure.

----
Initial impression: Having ridden mainly Assos and Castelli bibs for the last several years, these Giordana have a different fit and feel. The FRC Pro uses more material that what I am used to in those other brands. The legs feel a little bit longer, the bib straps are wider, and overall, the designers did not seem to be concerned with paring down weight (excess material). Pros and cons to this. This would not be my first choice for summer shorts because they feel a bit heavier (like heavy clothing, not like a significant weight penalty). The wider straps feel more secure, and less prone to buckle, pinch, or tear like some of the lightweight Castelli I have owned. However, the legs feel longer and the leg cuffs squeeze just behind the knees, therefore a bit more restrictive than necessary. The chamois also doesn't conform quite as well off the bike. The upper part of the chamois sort of pulls away from the body a bit (diaper effect). This is really only noticeable while standing; once on the bike the chamois lays down exactly where it needs to go, and it is on par in terms of comfort for at least the first few initial rides I have done with these. The chamois design looks very basic at this price point, that generic sort of orange/red foam I have seen on lower-line shorts, with stitching on the entire periphery. I am surprised that these are priced where they are. While sturdy and reliable, they feel a bit more economical because of these issues, and I would expect the FRC Pro to compete more directly with mid-level Pearl Izumi, for example, than with other top European brands. I am optimistic the bit of extra material will contribute to longevity, however, and if so, the price may be justified for my own personal sense of economy.
review.name: Adequate for the job. *

review.reviewBody:
I bought these bibs to add to my rotation and decided to spring for the best. Very comfortable top to bottom. Perfect chamois and comfy straps. 
Perfect compression where it is very supportive but not impossible to put on (I'm looking at you Castelli).
They fit true to size for me. I'm 5'8" tall, 155 pounds. I have size Medium.
The Bad: They wore through the inner thigh after 8 rides. As with all of my kits, I wash with gentle cycle and hang dry.
I own 10 pairs of bibs, mostly LG and Sportful. I have bibs that are over 5 years old and none have shown any wear on my inner thigh let alone worn through.
Sadly Competitive Cyclist won't let me return these. Perhaps they were defective because I want to love them. Hope this helps.
review.name: Fell in love then fell apart
comment: Same happened with me.  Sadly, I blew my budget on 2 pairs.  Both wore holes in the legs. In one pair, the entire chamois came unattached from the short.  Garbage. Wanted to love them.

review.reviewBody:
I've tried many bibs including Castelli, Rapha, and Assos. While those all seemed fine I would always experience some level of discomfort after a few hours in the saddle. The second I put these on I knew they were different. Everything just felt perfect. On top of a few centuries, the latest testament was 5 hours of a knarly, bumpy gravel race with zero chafing or discomfort. 

Now they're my go to bib. I use the others for shorter rides until I can replace them with a full rotation of these beauties. Do yourself a favor and get them now!
review.name: When you know, you know.

review.reviewBody: I have now had 3 pair of these. When I started cycling 2 years ago I needed an xl, my latest were a size medium and they fit perfectly. I have several of the supposed best brands, but I keep coming back to these because they are by far my most durable bibs. Chamois is as good as they come from my experience. Leg cuffs don't go floppy like some other brands. I can still wear my XL(chamois is just a bit large).  Straps are very comfortable as well. Highly recommend.
review.name: Excellent Bib

review.reviewBody: On my first ride with these, I actually noticed how nice they feel. They moved with me and just felt really nice. I found myself actually thinking about how nice they feel, and I washed them right away so that I could wear them again on my next ride. I highly recommend them.
review.name: Feels like another layer of skin

review.reviewBody: Just got these bibs and my initial impression is great. Fit and finish is very good, and the chamois was comfortable in a 2hr ride. The material seems to be on the thinner side but very compressive.
review.name: Good compression, fit and finish

review.reviewBody: I wore these for about two weeks straight while exploring Peru which involved lots of hiking through uneven, rocking terrain. They were comfortable and had good ankle support. Also, it was a true to size fit for me which was surprising since I was worried about my feet swelling at high altitudes and them being too small.

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I sized up one size so I could wear thicker socks with these shoes. Very comfortable out of the box. Great support doing yard work and walking wooded trail. Feet stayed dry inside and out!
review.name: Comfy and good support

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
These are way too narrow for my feet, which is a shame, since I really like my keen sandals because of how well they fit my foot. Just having them on while sitting scrunched my feet and made them uncomfortable. I’ve never had to wear a wide shoe before. 
I will be returning these, as the sole itself seems to narrow (so problem would be continuous, even if the synthetic upper stretched). Size was correct for the length of the shoe. 
Disappointed, because they seem great otherwise.
review.name: Too narrow for normal width feet

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody:
These hiking shoes are light weight and breathable.
The fit is nice and comfortable. They are my 2nd pair.
review.name: Terradora II

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I hiked the Indian Staircase at Red River Gorge. I loved the support. The fit was great. I have fibromyalgia I only say that to say. We hiked for 5-6 hrs and my feet only started to ache the last 30-45 mins. It still had nothing to do with the boots.
review.name: I hiked the Indian Staircase

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: It was time to replace my old Terradora hiking boots, so I decided to get a new version, and wasn't disappointed. The last pair lasted for 5 years before they weren't waterproof anymore. Which is great, because I work on a hydroponic farm and get water splashed on me daily. They're lightweight compared to other boots, and even though they're waterproof, they're still breathable! Size was great, fit is amazing as always. Overall a great shoe!
review.name: Great shoes!

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I got my shoes and they had two left inserts and then after calling to get it fixed I received crappy ones that were not similar to the original that came with the shoes. They were ones that I needed to cut myself and were thin and nothing like the gel ones.
review.name: Received the wrong insoles

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Wow! It’s been a long time since I bought new hiking shoes and they have come a long way. Very comfortable, versatile, and waterproof.
review.name: Wow!

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: Love these as much as I do the ones bought in winter—same exact style—but 1/2 size different. I was training for an upcoming hiking trip and was experiencing discomfort with the smaller size purchased, worn and enjoyed in winter on moderate weather days. The new pair is working much better for me on my hikes, including steep inclines and declines in pouring rain. They clean up well and go back to work the next day!
review.name: Remember to size up in summer

review.itemreviewed: Terradora II Mid WP Hiking Boot - Women's
review.reviewBody: I wear hiking boots as my daily drivers. The tread on these is enough if a random hike breaks out but isn’t excessive for my normal out and about. The two hooks for lacing make it a little less easy to put on compared to my other Keens but not a deal breaker.
review.name: Great everyday hiker

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody:
Love this bike seat. My son has so much fun going for rides. It's solid and easy to install. 

Though because I have a mountain bike, I had to modify it a bit to fit, but it wasn't hard at all.

A few reviews here say it doesn't fit, but all you have to do is take the housing off of the front part of the bracket. Once you've done that, it fits perfectly to any style of bike. 

It of course does change the normal riding feel and your turning radius is lower, but this isn't supposed to be able to handle what you would normally do on your maintain bike.

I've added a picture of the bracket on the bike for reference. The metal part of the front of the bracket pops right out with a flat head screw driver and you're good to go.
review.name: Great seat and easy to install.

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: Product will not attach to front mount. GOt to mount once and figured it was fine. Took out for the beginning of this year and the seat will not attach the to mounting bracket. Support was next to useless and refuses to issue a refund since the product was order over 30 days ago, but the product is clearly defective. Avoid this company like the plague.
review.name: Terrible product with even worse support

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: I bought this seat after much research for my very first grandson. The seat fits his body perfectly. It goes on and off the bike in under 10 seconds. It gives the parents added security of having their arms wrapped around the baby. The harness is childproof, and almost adult proof. My grandson smiled immediately upon being placed in the seat. Having the option of buying a second mounting kit made it easy to switch between my son and daughter-in-law‘s bike. I don’t believe they had these when my son was a baby. Having a baby in front is definitely a perk and a great safety feature. My son and his family loved their Christmas present this year and I did too.
review.name: The PERFECT bike seat for a child!

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody:
I've used this a couple times with our 10 month old, he loves it, it's secure, I feel that he's safe and it allows us to get out and ride on dirt (mostly fireroads). 

My issues are 1. there is no space for my knees (I'm on a full suspension mountain bike) and there doesn't seem to be a way to correct for this, its just the design of the seat and bike geometry. I can still ride, but have to have my knees out wide, after a couple miles, they hurt, long term there's potential to really jack with your knees. 
2. You do lose A LOT of turning radius up front. We aren't riding singletrack with the offspring yet so it's not a huge deal, but it's very restrictive. 

Because of these, I've honestly considered just riding with bebe in a backpack instead and/or waiting until he's older for a cockpit style seat.
review.name: Solidly okay - no room for knees

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: Bought Oct 2023. Used several times. Works fantastic. You keep the child in front of you between your arms. 10 month old of 22lbs and 31” loves it. Padding on handhold is not very durable—a teether chewed through quickly. We mounted a toy there for him. It does slightly limit your steering mobility; but that is fine because you aren’t making aggressive turns with the child. It is much better for an infant than a rear seat….he doesn’t feel alone and you have full control and visibility. Very fast shipping.
review.name: Excellent Seat

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: Pretty useless when you have to go shopping for a bike to fit the seat. Was able to attach the adapter, but it puts the seat at a 45 degree angle...so the kid is basically laying down and you can't ride the bike. Unable to use with a mountain bike. Thule will respond saying it's for "cruiser" bikes...which basically refers to outdated stem/headset designs. Don't waste your time/money unless you're confident it'll fit.
review.name: Poor design does not fit most bikes
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on the Thule Yepp Mini. I understand it is frustrating that your bike is not compatible with this bike seat.
The Thule Yepp Mini is indeed compatible with cruisers, but it also works with a wide range of hybrid and commuter-style bikes. Mountain bikes usually have a thicker front stem and shorter handlebar clearance that prevents a secure connection with the bike seat. Additionally, the most common use of mountain bikes - high speed, technical terrain - is not recommended for child bike seats. 
You may be able to connect your Thule Yepp Mini to your mountain bike using the Thule Yepp Ahead Stem Adapter, though you will still need the compatible stem clearance and stem diameter listed in the FAQ "How do I know if a Yepp or RideAlong child bike seat will fit my bike?"
https://help.thule.com/s/article/How-do-I-know-if-a-Yepp-or-RideAlong-child-bike-seat-will-fit-my-bike-en-us?language=en_US

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: Awesome product. Easy to connect to my trek bike, and most of all it’s a breeze. My daughter is almost 1 and I don’t have any problem maneuvering the bike w/ her in it and she absolutely loves the wind in her face.
review.name: Easier than anticipated

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody:
I've got a large Salsa Timberjack, after measuring the stem was PRAYING that his beautiful little seat would fit my bike, low and behold IT DOES.

Let me just check off the other questions/fears I had before purchasing:

Will I need to adjust my knees around the seat while pedalling?
- I'm 6'0" (183cm) tall, NO issues with my knees.

Will the stems from HER handlebars conflict with the front fork of my bike? 
- NO, but juuuuust barely.

Will my daughter (14mo at time time of posting) love this thing?
- She absolutely loves it


I'm overjoyed that my bike was able to accommodate the seat. I will say, a bike with a more upright riding position would be ideal for this seat, w/ the Timberjack I do need to sort of hunch my chest to accommodate my daughters helmet, but it's not so uncomfortable that I don't want to ride, and we're only out for 30-60min at a time, doing local paved/crusher fine gravel trails. For any casual ride, I don't think you can beat this seat.
review.name: LOVE This little seat

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody: Awesome product, easy to use, kiddo loves it. Rides great, even on moderate blue trails.
review.name: Best bike seat for trails

review.itemreviewed: Chariot Yepp Mini Front Child Bike Seat
review.reviewBody:
I’ve been using the Yepp mini with our child unsuccessfully with 2 different bikes. 
The seat leaves almost no space to dismount from the bike and stand astride the frame. So it’s ok if you’re on a path or a place where you don’t need to stop or pause for cars / stoplights. But as a commuter seat its unmanageable for our family. 

Our 1 year old does love being up front and it’s great talking to him about what we see on rides. But there’s no way for us to ride safely. We’ve tried with a MTB, and a single speed steel frame MASI, but both left so much to be desired. 

Only buy if you have a step through frame.
review.name: Wanted it to work so badly!
comment:
Thank you for sharing your feedback on the Thule Yepp Mini child bike seat. I'm sorry it did not meet the needs of your family and bikes. 
Thule bike seats have rather particular fitments to ensure a safe transport for children and rider. Unfortunately, some bikes do not provide a safe or comfortable ride due to their size and geometry. For more information on the suggested bike dimensions for different Thule bike seats, please see the FAQ page below. 
https://help.thule.com/s/article/How-do-I-know-if-a-Yepp-or-RideAlong-child-bike-seat-will-fit-my-bike-en-us?language=en_US

review.reviewBody: I'm a lefty. Bought 1 L & 1 R pair, installed R cage on seat tube, inverted facing forward. Both now oriented for Lefty. Perfect solution. Road Mickelson Trail in SD with hilly side trip to Mt. Rushmore. They hold bottles securely, though I don't subject to MTB riding. They've held up well, despite being plastic. I anticipate long life under my use. Recommended, given the price point and availability as L-R pair.
review.name: Lefty-Righty Cages do the Job

review.reviewBody: Ok value for the price but doesn't hold my bottle securely. Not worth the headache to return the item. I do not recommend this item.

review.reviewBody: So, there is a specific cage that the manufacturer of my bike recommends, and it's a really nice carbon side-loader. Nothing against that cage, but if you're trying to save dollars and not grams...the Flow SL is the best bang for your buck. It holds the bottle perfectly over rough, chunky terrain and yet the bottle is still easy enough to grab when needed. Maybe someday, I'll swap it over to a light weight cage that echos the level of craftsmanship on my bike and saves some weight. Until then, this thing works perfectly fine!
review.name: Value priced side-loading cage

review.reviewBody: I have a tight triangle on my full suspension bike (YT IZZO) and needed a cage which would fit a small/squat bottle and allow me to pull it out from the side rather than the top. This fit the bill perfectly.
review.name: Great design and value

review.reviewBody: Looks nice, and is easy-on and off.  I ordered the R side.  It's important to note, this will come out the right if mounted on the downtube and the left if mounted on the seat tube.
review.name: R on downtube, L on seat tube

review.reviewBody: Love the cage. Purchased the hyper green. Color matches perfectly with my Specialized 5.0 Ordering the left hand model too.
review.name: Great Cage

review.reviewBody: Well, hopefully this is the goofiest employee review I'll ever write. We were running a little low on cages, and I saw this one came in purple, and honestly kind of impulse bought it. Lo and behold, I did not think the situation through at all. I got it on my bike yesterday and went to see if I could grab my bottle while riding, so I could report back on the quality and ease of use. Unfortunately, all I can report is that I ride left handed, and I bought myself a left-entry bottle cage ? so that's pretty much a complete bust. I leaned down and ended up with a handful of bottle cage and no bottle. It did keep a solid hold on the bottle, though! Seemed like it would be pretty easy to operate if you get the correct entry side; the plastic has a nice little bit of flex to it. It also fits super nicely on my tiny XS frame. Just double check which is your dominant hand before ordering.
review.name: Try To Remember If You're A Lefty

review.reviewBody:
It’s a game changer. For the very first time tire itself works without applying brakes all the time. On the very easy turns I just can go. On sharp one brakes are required for sure but I can sense how tire works and just holds the line. Grip is amazing. 
I do like climbing and weight is not the issue. I did not notice significant problem with going up even though tire is definitely heavier than my previous XC one. However downhill rides are awesome. 
My current setup is assegai 2.5wt front/dhr II 2.4wt rear.
Rims are 29 i27 and no issues whatsoever

review.reviewBody:
The title of the tire here says "Wide Tire 3C Maxxterra EXO."  If this is that tire, its claimed weight is 1,082.  

If it is a Double Down tire, it's not titled that way. The 3C-TR-DD tire weighs 1,395 claimed. 

So, the titles are wrong and the claimed weights are incorrect. But which tire are you selling in the ad? Is that the DD tire or the EXO tire, which is not DD?

review.reviewBody: This was a gift for my boyfriend for Christmas! I gave it to him early and he loved it, was even wearing it around the house. He tried to fill up the water bladder and it busted open at the seem between the handle and bag part! We weren’t even able to take it outside yet. I’ve used the exact same bladder for over a year with no problems so maybe this one was defective. I tried filling a report and contacting Gregory. They said they would contact me about it by two days but I haven’t heard back.
review.name: Defective water bladder

review.reviewBody: Very good day bag. The frame and suspended airflow system is miles better than Osprey's useless Airscape system and far less bulky than the comparable suspended Airspeed system. When using the water bladder, you are left with one main pocket that could use a bit more internal organization, along with the small upper pocket, hip-belt pockets, and mesh. The chest clip system is annoying - rather than a traditional buckle, it is some sort of hook-and-magnet system that is impossible to undo with one hand without also loosening the strap. Conversely, it is challenging to loosen the strap without accidentally undoing the clip. Also, the tube that comes with the included bladder is too short to use without bending your neck awkwardly.
review.name: Very good day hiking bag, some minor quibbles.

review.reviewBody: I absolutely love this pack so far. It was comfortable on my first hike. The wire frame and suspension allow the pack to remain comfortable no matter how horrible you cram everything into the pack. The separate hydration pocket is great along with the side stuff pockets and hip belt pockets.
review.name: The perfect day pack does exist!

review.reviewBody: Just got this bag in and I’m thrilled! Amazing quality, design and very lightweight. I love the clip feature across the chest and the support on your back is great. If you’re looking for a new water pack this is it!
review.name: AMAZING BAG FOR EVERYTHING OUTDOOR

review.reviewBody: I have problem feet and have for years.  Basically I’m flat footed and have bunions on both feet.  Shoes with too high of an arch built in cut into my foot and throw my foot off to the opposite side of the shoe.  These have just enough of an arch to give me support and also are just wide enough to float over my bunions, never irritating them.  I have all colors of these.
review.name: Love these shoes!
comment: Thank you for your wonderful review!

review.reviewBody: I’ve been wearing Siren Sport 2 then 3 for many years. I was very excited to see Siren 4 because they look so pretty. I purchased a pair, but had to return. Although it feels very comfortable, the back of the right one was too high and it hurts my right ankle. Eventually, I found a 3 somewhere else. Would you please make a Siren that is as comfortable as 3 and as pretty as 4?
review.name: Hurts my right ankle

review.reviewBody: After owning four pairs of Merrill, shoes, I found this pair online and purchased for a vacation to the beach. I took my first walk around five km, and found the foot bed to have minimal support. The rubberized base and toe cap, did not allow for ventilation making the footwear extremely hot. The shoes look great as all Merrill, footwear.
review.name: Hot footwear

review.reviewBody:
Love the colors, love the grip
They fit large though.  I checked other merrells and their size guide which suggested 8 or 8.5. I got a 7.5 as I am normally a 7 but the guide suggested a full size larger.  They are too big.
review.name: Try them on in person if you can
comment: We're sorry your Merrells didn't fit as expected, but we appreciate your feedback.

review.reviewBody: I've been wearing the Siren Sport line since 2012. After being unable to find my usual Siren Sport 3 listing, I found these. I was eager to try out the new insoles included as since the OrthoLite Comfort Foam has stopped being carried, I've needed to get insoles elsewhere. Upon opening the box, I noticed they looked very narrow. When I went to try them on, there was no way my foot was getting in them. Apparently these don't come in a wider width so I can't try that. Luckily, the day after I purchased these, I received an email to review the Siren Sport 3 and was able to purchase my size. Put my new 3s on after trying these and whadda ya know? Perfect fit.
review.name: Siren line this is not

review.reviewBody:
I bought the Siren 4 shoe about 2 weeks ago and was only able to wear them once. There must be a defect with the shoe as the right shoe has what appears to be a wire that sticks out under the collar and digs in to my right ankle. It was very painful, so I could not wear them for very long. They also have no grip. In the short amount of time that I wore them I fell twice due to the slippery sole. I own The North Face shoes and have used them for hiking many times without any issues. I will stick to that brand from
Now on. 

I called Merrell about the problem with the shoes and unfortunately they won’t issue a refund.
review.name: Painful and slippery

review.reviewBody:
Bought these and have been wearing. They definitely run BIG. Gonna size down 1/2 size and give the larger ones away.
Been wearing Sirens for years, first time I ever had a sizing issue. Merrell needs to upgrade their quality department apparently…

comment: We're sorry to hear this did not work out for you. We appreciate your feedback and if we can help please give us a call at 800-288-3124. Thank you.

review.reviewBody: Not sure if got pair incorrectly labelled re: size as fit at least 1/2 size larger than Siren 3. Tread is great and sole is soft and comfy, however, collar of shoe is not well padded and quite stiff. Shoe has a nice look.

review.reviewBody: I bought this to use for skate skiing in below freezing temps. It doesn't get super cold here, usually operating between 20–30 degrees F. The front of the vest provides excellent protection from wind and keeps your core comfortable while allowing heat exhaust from the thinner back panel. The fit is trim—I purchased a medium based on the on-model fit notes and am happy with the fit for activewear, but cannot wear this as a casual layer over a flannel or looser fitting long sleeve. It fits snug and streamlined. I am 6'1" and 175lbs with a longer torso. If you're between two sizes and intend to use it at a crossover or hybrid piece, I suggest sizing up. review.itemreviewed: Ivalo 3 Classic BUGrip Winter Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
This will be my 2nd pair of Ice Bugs and I absolutely love them. I'd fallen 4 times the winter before I got my 1st pair while wearing conventional "cleats" and didn't fall at all after I wore Ice Bugs the following winter. (I live in Alaska). I feel so secure while walking with them. I haven't actually worn this particular pair because they just arrived today & one of the zippers was completely stuck. I could not get it to work so am having to return them for another pair. The one boot I was able to get on appeared to fit well and feels soft and comfy.  They also look nice. I'm a woman who wear's men's sizes since most companies don't offer women's size 12.
I guess this is more a review for Ice Bugs in general but if you live in any kind of winter climate they're worth it!
review.name: Great boots but defective zipper

review.itemreviewed: Ivalo 3 Classic BUGrip Winter Boot - Men's
review.reviewBody:
These are so worth the money!  
We live in the woods in Michigan, an area that freezes and thaws often throughout the winter season, ice is a constant issue.   
Since foot surgery several years ago, I haven't been as stable on my feet & fear the ice (having fallen often & getting older).  I  had to limit my outdoor activities.
These boots are so stable and the support is superior  - I'm back to long hikes through the woods and feel safe while doing chores around the house - collecting firewood, and feeding & cleaning our chickens.
Great Boots!
review.name: Life Saver &  Comfortable!!

I loathe camping with a passion unbridled. I love coffee brewed in the manners that bring out the natural flavors of the variety and the microclimate of the fair-trade plantation where the beans are grown. Yeah, I know, that sounds very snobbish and pretentious.

But, coffee should be experienced and savored, not just drunk out a pot that has been stewing for who knows how long from a gas station or even a coffee shop.  Pour over coffee is a means to that end. This  system does exactly that. 

My only gripe is that this system like all metal filters does not filter all of the grounds. Inevitably there is then a bit of sludge in the bottom of the cup. Otherwise, This system is excellent for both brewing coffee and keeping it hot for a long, long time.

review.reviewBody: I love this jacket. It's the perfect weight for so many activities and I love the cut. I'm 5'6" and 130lbs and I have a small. Fits perfect. I tried to buy another one but they have been out of stock forever. If they sell smalls again I will buy a new one.

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: I love this jacket and I get so many compliments on the color (caribou). It's great on it's own as a sunny day nordic ski jacket or as a mid-layer for colder downhill skiing. I'm normally a Medium and got the Small for a more fitted look, but if you want to layer it over more thank a tank, get your normal size. My only complaint is that it shows a lot of wear and pilling after just one season, which is disappointing. Probably won't last through many more seasons and still look good.
review.name: Love it but shows wear

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: This jacket fits true to size and worked for me on cold morning walks or runs at temps of low 20s and low 30s.

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: I'm 5'8'' 130lbs and the Small is a perfect fit. It's warm but allows me to cool off while I exercise and the cut is flattering for me. So glad I made this purchase!
review.name: LOVE it!

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: I’m 5’11” 145lbs. I ordered the large in brown and love it so much I’m ordering the black. Super flexible and ultra lightweight. I could probably wear a medium but like to layer and like the long sleeves.
review.name: Great all around jacket.

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: Was so excited to get this today to wear this weekend but will sadly be returning this since it is too tight in the arm pits where I couldn’t put my arms down! The chest area was also way too tight. Not sure if this was a defect but I would SIZE UP.  I purchased XS. For reference I’m 5ft 98lbs, 32B, slender.
review.name: Well made but weird fit and way too smal

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: I have done everything in this jacket this season from winter trail running to downhill skiing and I love it!!! It keeps you warm while not compromising on breathability and not restricting movement. This jacket pairs well under ski wear as well as with running vests and back packs. So many winter insulated jackets are hooded so I really appreciate the hoodless feature here. I am typically a size small and find this size small fits well, it's an athletic fit, which I prefer for high output activities.
review.name: The Most Versatile Insulated Jacket

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: ...my winter workout jacket. I love it for wearing around but i'm super excited to wear this for winter trail running, and nordic skiing as well as a mid-layer for downhill skiing. I love that they changed the breathable fabric to a soft fleece. I'm 5'2" 119lbs and got the size small. I'm below average height so this sits longer on me than where it sits on the models in the photos. But that's normal for me. LOL
review.name: This is my everyday fall jacket and...

review.itemreviewed: Teo Hybrid ALLIED Down Jacket - Women's
review.reviewBody: This jacket is SO CUTE on the models!  The website stated that the models were 6' tall and 5'8" tall and they both were wearing size Small.  I'm 5'5" so I ordered an XS.  It was MUCH too small and "cut" into my underarms.
review.name: Wanted to love it!

review.reviewBody: Bought a few of these and the gate tension is higher than any biner I have. Spring is snappy though. The nice gate shape still makes it easy to operate with just a thumb. Less snaggy and better handling than BD biners. I would dock a star but since this is the best biner in this size and class, it still deserves 5 stars.
review.name: Stiff gate but still handles decently

review.reviewBody: I use these for all my MasterCams plus several alpine draws and love them for the price. The nose snags sometimes, but no more than other non-keynose carabiners that I have. Really consistent QC on these compared to some of my other carabiners (looking at you BD Oz). Also prefer these to the few Metolius Mini II's I have. I find the Nano easier to work with for some reason and don't really notice the size, whereas I reeeeally notice the small size of the Mini II's and have to fiddle with them more.
review.name: Light, small, narrow, cheap

review.reviewBody: These are super light and I used them to rack my gear on my harness as well as for alpine draws. The lightest and slim profile make them ideal for this use. The wire gate does have a nose that will catch on your gear loops or rope when taking them off, which can be annoying.
review.name: The lightest full strength carabiner

review.reviewBody: Smaller and lighter, just what you're probably after. The big issue I have with this carabiner is that where the wire gate attaches to the body, it's sharp and sits off the body. It catches on slings and other gear and can wreck a dyneema sling. But, if it doesn't catch on stuff or isn't sitting with soft gear, you're good to go and will probably never notice.
review.name: Wire can catch on gear

review.reviewBody: I ordered this fleece over 2 weeks before Mother’s Day as a gift for my mom. After following up with backcountry on two different occasions, a package was delivered a several days after Mother’s Day. The package contained the wrong jacket. When I asked them to fix the mistake and overnight the right jacket, they insisted I ask my mother to package and return the jacket sent by mistake or pay for that jacket as well. The fact that they would ask to have my mother do this after completely screwing up the entire order is lousy customer service.
review.name: Disappointing customer service

review.reviewBody: My normal size is small. This fits very tight especially in the arm and pit area and my arms are not even big. My arms are very slim. I should’ve gotten medium had I known these jackets run small. Now they didn’t have size M in the floor I want. Mb I’ll keep small and deal with tightness in the arm area. Note to self- with these jackets, size up. I also ordered the same version in vest in size small, which is also very tight and small. Luckily I was able to exchange vest to medium.
review.name: Runs small/ tight fitting

This is the 3rd Patagonia Better Sweater I have bought. All 3 are Mediums and all 3 fit different. One is tight fitting.

review.reviewBody: I’ve owned for a year with no issues regarding the quality. I’m always cold in the winter but find that this keeps me warm. I’m 5’3” 130lb and bought a small. It fit perfectly when I got it, but I think it has shrunk a touch after several washes. I could see where it might be tight in the arms/chest for some but that’s not a problem I ever have. I would size up if you’re in doubt.

review.reviewBody: I expected a lot more from Patagonia given the price for a FLEECE jacket. The inside isn’t soft, it runs small and there’s just no justification for the price and quality. I’m 5’7, weigh 130 pounds and the small fit snug and the arm length is short (I’m used to this given my height). Point is… I have better quality Colombia jackets and North Face jackets that I’ve gotten cheaper. Also, BackCountry doesn’t do free returns so keep that in mind.

review.reviewBody:
I bought this sweater in September as a birthday present, less than three months ago & the zipper broke. Backcountry said I’m outside their return policy & to go to Patagonia-not a fun situation.

review.reviewBody: I ordered this for my favorite fisherman’s birthday as he loved the blue one he already had. This is the same shirt style but apparently made by a different manufacturer now.  The logo on the white fishing shirt has Simms on the front and a fish on the back. The blue fishing shirt has fish on the front and Simms on the back. The blue fishing shirt has two buttons at the bottom of the sleeve, the white has one button. That being said, the sleeve cuffs are too loose. The back and chest fit are too tight on the white one, the blue one couldn’t fit nicer. Do better Simms, this is disappointing.
review.name: Poor consistency in sizing and detail.

review.reviewBody: I wore this shirt in hot sticky Florida for a week.  It was very cool, comfortable,  and looked good too.  Many worthwhile features which justify the price over the cheaper competition - including little things like reinforced fabric at shirt sleeve buttons for roll up wear.  This shirt will last.  I ordered 2 more (white and blue) because they will take care me in the sunshine - reducing cancer risk all year around.  I like my gray one, but I do wish they made it in a lighter blue color, and maybe a light yellow too.  Fits great on my average build.  I do not tuck in my casual shirts.  The hem length on these  is perfect and wearing them out is cooler and more comfortable.  Other similar shirts look baggy not tucked in.
Awesome shirt , great sun protection & very comfortable
review.name: Shiry

review.reviewBody: What a great fitting, comfortable, and durable shirt.  This is a shirt you can wear fishing all day long or wear it out on the town.  I get many compliments on all of my Simms clothing, but I get a lot more when I wear this line of shirts.  I highly recommend this shirt!!
review.name: Great fit, comfortable, durable, and versatile.

Italy because I wanted to be able to take only one pair of boots with me and I needed comfort because I knew we’d be walking ALOT! review.reviewBody: I bought these boots specifically for my 2 week trip to Italy. I walked so much daily (over 20,000 steps owe day) and climbed so many steps and my feet never felt tired or sore. They looked cute with jeans, leggings, slacks & skirts.
review.name: So comfy, stylish and great quality

review.reviewBody: I bought the wrong size so it was returned. review.name: Cute but stiff

review.reviewBody:
This is the perfect commuting backpack. The Airspeed frame keeps the pack off your back. I'm able to pack my clothes for the day, a pair of shoes, a jersey for the ride home (if it's a cooler morning), and my lunch. Packing all this does take some creativity but there's certainly plenty of room for the light packing commuter. I don't use the hydration bladder but I have the same bladder/hose on a different pack and I know from experience that it's pretty rad. I do wish there was some better retention for the loose straps as they tend to flap around in the wind. I'd knock half a star for that but since it's a whole star reviewing system, they get to keep the 5. 

TL;DR: This is a great pack for a light packing commuter.
review.name: Perfect Commuter Pack

review.reviewBody: [This review was collected as part of a promotion.] I've been using my Syncro 12 hydration pack on longer rides and find it to be more comfortable than any back pack I've used for riding. Couldn't be more pleased.
